
Write me a database schema for a new Postgres-based version of the task tracker. It should have
three main tables/abstractions:

1. **Commits** are git commits: they have associated with them a repository (identified by path;
   I don't believe we need anything more than this, since any additional information about the
   repo we can obtain by invoking git in that path). Each commit has a series of attributes:

    * its jj change ID, which we should store in the database since it will be lost if the commit
      gets garbage collected
    * its *review status*, which should be one of unreviewed, approved, rejected
    * a boolean "should run CI", which starts as false but which the software should set to true
      when the user approves a commit
    * its *CI status*, which should be one of unstarted, failed, passed, skipped
    * its **commit type**, which is one of normal, tip, single, or merge

2. A **pull request** is a set of commits, exactly one of which is the "tip". Each PR also has a
   review status (unreview, approved, rejected) as well as an integer priority, and a "ready for
   merge" boolean which indicates that the PR should be merged as soon as all checks have passed.

3. A **stack** is a set of merge commits that are ready to be pushed. Each stack has a series of
   jj change IDs representing merge commits, each one building on the next. A stack may be pushed
   or cancelled.

4. There should also be a log table which logs each action with a description, reason and timestamp.
   For a given commit or PR or stack it should be possible to query all the logs about it.

The typical lifecycle of a PR is:

1. The user invokes a CLI tool to download the PR information from Forgejo or Github. A database
   entry for the PR is created, and ones for every commit in the PR are created. Every commit has
   the type "normal" except the tip which has type "tip".
2. Using the CLI, the user reviews each commit in order; when each commit is approved, it becomes
   ready for testing. The daemon should be constantly scanning for commits which are untested,
   and should start the test. If it passes, its CI status is set to passed.
3. Once all the commits in a PR have been approved and passed, the user can mark the PR itself as
   approved, providing an ACK message to be posted. (When it is posted, we should also write the
   message as posted to the database in a separate row. The daemon should be scanning for ACKs that
   are not yet posted, and if the user later changes the ACK message, the new message should be
   posted.) The user can also mark the PR as "ready for merge", and/or set a threshold of required
   reviewers, and once enough of them have ACKed then the PR should automatically become ready
   for merge.
4. Once a PR is ready for merge, a merge commit should be created and put onto the appropriate
   stack (the one with the correct repo and target branch) (an empty one should be created if
   none exists). The merge commit should be identified by its change ID, not its commit ID! If
   the description of a commit changes or it is signed, this should not invalidate any CI tests.
5. The daemon will test the commits in a stack; any commit(s) which pass tests should be signed
   by the user out-of-band; and any commits which have been passed and signed should be pushed.
6. If the target branch of a stack changes (e.g. because of another push) then the whole stack
   should be cancelled and its merge commits recreated (with new change IDs), *except* that if
   a stack is partially pushed, then its remaining commits should stay in the stack. (This will
   happen if the user signs some but not all of the commits in a stack.)

Please ask for clarifying questions before producing any real output.

Furthermore, suggest other design documents that can be used to guide a LLM into architecting
the software; identify parts of this system that likely need a detailed design.


